(a) Comparison of randomly ordered particle occupancy (red squares)
and sequentially ordered particle occupancy (blue circles). Sequential
ordering consistently produces lower execution times throughout the
evaluated particle range. At the largest benchmark configuration,
random ordering incurs an execution-time penalty of approximately
\nc{Locality Penalty}, demonstrating the importance of memory locality
despite identical algorithmic complexity.

(b) Log--log throughput as a function of particle count for the total
application (red), compute stage (blue), and graphics stage (black).
Dashed vertical lines indicate transitions between utilization,
saturation, and throughput-limited regimes. Throughput saturates for
$N>\numprint{\APQBRTIMEPERPALLstartval{}}$.

(c) Time-per-particle for the graphics, compute, and total application
stages for $N\geq\numprint{\APQBRTIMEPERPALLstartval{}}$, corresponding
to the saturated throughput regime. The graphics stage stabilizes at
\APQBRTIMEPERPALLGraphicsstabilzes{}$\pm$\APQBRTIMEPERPALLGraphicsstdval{}
ns/particle, the compute stage at
\APQBRTIMEPERPALLComputestabilzes{}$\pm$\APQBRTIMEPERPALLComputestdval{}
ns/particle, and the total application at
\APQBRTIMEPERPALLTotalstabilzes{}$\pm$\APQBRTIMEPERPALLTotalstdval{}
ns/particle.